    "# 💻 Syndicate 3.0: Phase 9 Playroom (Bare Metal Apple Silicon)\n",
    "\n",
    "Running state-of-the-art models on consumer-grade hardware (like your MacBook's Apple Silicon) requires extreme memory efficiency. We cannot load 32-bit floats for billions of weights into unified RAM. We must **compress** them using **Quantization**.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this playroom, you will master the linear algebra and math behind **4-bit Min-Max Quantization** using pure Python primitives, demonstrating how neural weights are squeezed and reconstructed with minimal loss.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## ⚖️ 9.1: Weight Quantization Arithmetic\n",
    "\n",
    "### 🧪 Discovery Lab: The Quantization Compression Mechanics\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose we have a set of neural weights in a model layer:\n",
    "$$\\mathbf{W} = [0.8732, -0.1245, 0.5511]$$\n",
    "\n",
    "We want to compress these 32-bit floats into 4-bit integers (ranging from `0` to `15`) so they occupy $8\\times$ less space in VRAM.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 1. The Naive Attempt (Basic Rounding)\n",
    "Let's round these weights to the nearest integer."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "weights = [0.8732, -0.1245, 0.5511]\n",
    "rounded = [round(w) for w in weights]\n",
    "print(f\"Rounded weights: {rounded}\")\n",
    "# Look at the output. All variance is gone. The weights have collapsed into just two values. The model is brain-dead."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### 2. The Mathematical/Logical Necessity\n",
    "Instead of rounding absolute values, we must dynamically map the real-numbered range $[W_{\\min}, W_{\\max}]$ to our discrete 4-bit range $[0, 15]$. \n",
    "We calculate a **Scale Factor ($S$)** based on the difference between the minimum and maximum weights, shift the weights so they start at 0, divide by $S$, and round to the nearest integer. To use the weights, we perform the inverse operation to dequantize them.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 3. The Rosetta Stone (Linear Min-Max Quantization)\n",
    "$$S = \\frac{W_{\\max} - W_{\\min}}{15}$$\n",
    "$$\\text{Quantize}(W) = \\text{round}\\left(\\frac{W - W_{\\min}}{S}\\right)$$\n",
    "$$\\text{Dequantize}(Q) = (Q \\times S) + W_{\\min}$$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from typing import List, Tuple\n",
    "\n",
    "# TODO: Implement 4-bit min-max quantization in pure Python\n",
    "def quantize_4bit(weights: List[float]) -> Tuple[List[int], float, float]:\n",
    "    w_min = min(weights)\n",
    "    w_max = max(weights)\n",
    "    # Calculate scale factor for 16 discrete slots (0 to 15)\n",
    "    scale = 0.0\n",
    "    \n",
    "    quantized = []\n",
    "    return quantized, scale, w_min\n",
    "\n",
    "# TODO: Implement dequantization\n",
    "def dequantize_4bit(quantized: List[int], scale: float, w_min: float) -> List[float]:\n",
    "    return []\n",
    "\n",
    "original_weights = [0.8732, -0.1245, 0.5511]\n",
    "quantized, scale, w_min = quantize_4bit(original_weights)\n",
    "reconstructed = dequantize_4bit(quantized, scale, w_min)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Quantized values (4-bit integers): {quantized}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Reconstructed floats: {reconstructed}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# The reconstruction should be extremely close to the original values\n",
    "for orig, recon in zip(original_weights, reconstructed):\n",
    "    assert abs(orig - recon) < 0.05, f\"Loss too high: {orig} vs {recon}\"\n",
    "print(\"Success! 4-bit min-max quantization and dequantization verified.\")"
